Bg4 7. h3 (or 7. d3 Qd7 8. Be3 h5 9. h4 O-O-O 10. Qe2 g5 11. hxg5 fxg5 12. Bxg5 Be7 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Qe3 Ng6 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. f4 Nf7 17. e5 Rdg8 18. Ne4 Bh3 19. Rf2 Rh6 20. Kh2 Bf5 21. Qa7 Kd8 [Kroone,G-Euwe,M Amsterdam 1923 0-1])

?! - Was a little surprised to see this honestly. Willingly adding the queen to the pin. I expected 12. Rde1 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qc8
I initiate a plan to get rid of the other bishop, by disguising an attack on the vulnerable d4 square.
If white had seen what I was doing, then the proper response would have been 13. h3 Bh5.
The other reasons I wanted to exchange the knight off: add the missing link to my pawn chain and free up my bishop.

Passive movements like this had me wondering: did white ever have a plan of attack in this game? Defense is good, but with no effective counterpunching strategy, the battle will be over very quickly. I felt black had the positional edge here. Alternative variation: 19. c4 dxc3 20. bxc3 Rfd8, to at least break up the pawn chain a little bit and give white some breathing room.

Well here is what my opponent did, and here are the alternative options. Did you pick something I did not cover? Alternative variation #1: 25. bxc4 bxc4 26. Nxc4 (26. dxc4 Rxb2 [Discovered attack]) 26... Rxb2 [Discovered attack]
Alternative variation #2: 25. dxc4 bxc4 26. bxc4 (26. Nxc4 Bxc4 27. bxc4 Qc6 [Decoy Double attack] (27... Rxb2 [Remove defender Deflection Pinning])) 26... Rxb2 [Clearance Deflection Pinning]
With any of the options, you can clearly see that white was in serious trouble and positionally was on the verge of collapse. But this isn't how the game would end!
